STYLE="font-size:4px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">An increase in combined operating margin percent. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:4px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">An increase in return on average assets due primarily to a decrease in average asset balances. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:8px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
FACE="Arial" SIZE="2"><B>Highlights from the year included: </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:2px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">Comparable sales grew 6.9% and guest counts rose 3.1%, building on 2007 increases of 6.8% and 3.8%, respectively. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P
STYLE="font-size:2px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">Systemwide sales increased 11% (9% in constant currencies). </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:2px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">Company-operated margins improved to 17.6% and franchised margins improved to 82.3%. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P
STYLE="font-size:2px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">Net income per share from continuing operations was $3.76, an increase of 16% after adjusting for the impact of the 2007 Latin America transaction.
</FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:2px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">Cash provided by operations totaled $5.9 billion and capital expenditures totaled $2.1 billion. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE></DIV><DIV
STYLE="position:relative;float:right; width:48%;padding-right:9px;padding-bottom:8px;overflow:hidden">
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">Returned $5.8 billion to shareholders through shares repurchased and dividends paid, including a 33% increase in the quarterly cash dividend to $0.50 per share for the fourth
quarter &#150; bringing our current annual dividend rate to $2.00 per share. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:2px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">One-year ROIIC was 38.9% and three-year ROIIC was 37.5% for 2008. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:11px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial"
SIZE="2"><B>Outlook for 2009 </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:2px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">We will continue to drive success in 2009 and beyond by remaining focused on being better, not just bigger. We will do so by further
enhancing our understanding of consumers&#146; needs and wants; facilitating greater sharing and adoption of best practices and new ideas worldwide; and leveraging a strategic approach to implementing initiatives to drive the best bottom-line
impact. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:3%"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">Despite challenging economic conditions, the McDonald&#146;s System is energized by our current worldwide momentum. We will continue to build
on our strength in five key areas: maintaining the balance between price and value; maximizing the benefit of available capital by improving the relevance and contemporary feel of our existing restaurants; leveraging the equity and unique tastes of
core menu favorites like the Big Mac, the Quarter Pounder with Cheese and our world-famous French Fries; continuing our financial discipline and evaluation of success measures to ensure these measures are driving actions that positively impact our
restaurants; and furthering operations excellence by focusing on improved execution. As we do so, we are confident we can meet or exceed the long-term constant currency financial targets previously discussed. </FONT></P> <P
STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:3%"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">In the U.S., our 2009 focus is to continue to build relevance and loyalty by staying connected to customers&#146; needs for menu variety and beverage choice,
everyday affordability and convenience. Our initiatives will include reminding customers of the enduring appeal of menu classics such as the Big Mac and encouraging trial of new sandwich and beverage options including specialty coffees. Also in
2009, we will continue to offer value across our menu from the Dollar Menu to our premium products, as well as our classic menu favorites and mid-tier offerings such as our Double Cheeseburger and Snack Wraps. These initiatives combined with the
convenience of our locations, optimized drive-thru service, cashless transactions and longer operating hours will reinforce McDonald&#146;s position as our customers&#146; preferred place and way to eat. </FONT></P> <P
STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:3%"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">Our priorities in Europe remain upgrading the customer and employee experience, enhancing local relevance and building brand transparency. In 2009, we will continue
upgrading our restaurants&#146; ambiance through reimaging, including adding another 200 McCafes primarily in Germany and France. In addition, we will focus on optimizing our drive-thru service, completing the conversion of our kitchen operating
system in most European restaurants and increasing total locations offering extended and 24-hour service. We also will strengthen our local relevance by complementing our tiered menu with new products and a relevant variety of limited-time food
events featuring beef, chicken, desserts and coffee selections. In the area of brand transparency, we will remain open and accessible and will continue to inform consumers about our food quality and reputation as an employer. </FONT></P> <P
STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:3%"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">In APMEA, our goal is to be consumers&#146; first choice when eating out. To achieve this goal, locally-relevant strategies surrounding convenience, breakfast and
branded affordability are essential in this diverse and dynamic part of the world. Convenience initiatives include leveraging the success of 24-hour or extended operating hours, offering delivery service and building our drive-thru </FONT>
</P></DIV><br clear="All"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P>
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="1">14 </FONT></P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" COLOR="#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

<DIV STYLE="position:relative;float:left; margin-right:1%; width:48%;padding-right:9px;padding-bottom:8px;overflow:hidden"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">
<FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">traffic. We will also aggressively continue to open new restaurants in China. We will further build our breakfast business in APMEA by increasing the number of
locations where it is served, utilizing innovative marketing support and launching new products. At the same time, we will continue to highlight our classic menu favorites and offer locally-relevant extensions of these products. In addition, we are
further leveraging a strategic pricing tool to optimize menu prices to drive sales and profits. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:3%"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">In 2009, we will continue to optimize the mix of
franchised and Company-operated restaurants and will refranchise restaurants under the previously mentioned target. The speed with which we make progress toward this goal will depend on our ability to identify the appropriate prospective franchisees
with the experience and financial resources in the relevant markets. We will also continue to evaluate several small markets in APMEA and Europe for potential transition to developmental license structures. We will only convert such markets when we
believe that we have identified a qualified licensee and our business is ready for transition to optimize the transaction for the long-term. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:3%"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">As
previously discussed, our evolution toward a more heavily franchised, less capital-intensive business model has favorable implications for the amount of capital we invest, the strength and stability of our cash flow and our long-term returns. As a
result, we expect free cash flow &#151; cash from operations less capital expenditures &#151; will continue to grow and be a significant source to fund total cash returned to shareholders. In addition, we expect our share repurchase activity will
continue to yield reductions in our outstanding share count. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:3%"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">Finally, we will continue to be disciplined financially, remaining diligent about how
and where we invest capital and selling, general and administrative expenses to grow our business. Consistent with the last few years, to drive sales and returns we will allocate nearly 50% of our $2.1 billion of planned 2009 capital expenditures
toward reinvestments in existing restaurants, mainly related to the reimaging of locations in Europe and the rollout of the beverage strategy in the U.S. The remainder of our capital expenditures will primarily be used to build new locations.
</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:3%"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">McDonald&#146;s does not provide specific guidance on net income per share. The following information is provided to assist in analyzing the
Company&#146;s results: </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:4px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">Changes in Systemwide sales are driven by comparable sales and net restaurant unit expansion. The Company expects net restaurant additions to add nearly 2 percentage points
to 2009 Systemwide sales growth (in constant currencies), most of which will be due to the 709 net traditional restaurants added in 2008. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:4px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">The Company does not generally provide specific guidance on changes in comparable sales. However, as a perspective, assuming no change in cost structure, a 1 percentage point
increase in comparable sales for either the U.S. or Europe would increase annual net income per share by about 3 cents. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:4px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">With about 75% of McDonald&#146;s grocery bill comprised of 10 different commodities, a basket of goods approach is the most comprehensive way to look at the Company&#146;s
commodity costs. For the full year 2009, the total basket of goods is expected to rise about 5% to 5.5% in the U.S. and about 4% to 4.5% in Europe with more of this pressure occurring in the first half of the year. Some volatility may be experienced
between quarters in the normal course of business. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P></DIV><DIV
STYLE="position:relative;float:right; width:48%;padding-right:9px;padding-bottom:8px;overflow:hidden">
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">The Company expects full-year 2009 selling, general&nbsp;&amp; administrative expenses to decline, in constant currencies, although fluctuations may be experienced between
quarters due to certain items in 2008 such as the biennial Worldwide Owner/Operator Convention and the Beijing Summer Olympics. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:4px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">Based on current interest and foreign currency exchange rates, the Company expects interest expense in 2009 to be relatively flat compared with 2008. Interest income in 2009
is expected to decrease about 80% compared with 2008 due to expected lower average interest rates and average cash balances. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:4px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">A significant part of the Company&#146;s operating income is generated outside the U.S., and about 45% of its total debt is denominated in foreign currencies. Accordingly,
earnings are affected by changes in foreign currency exchange rates, particularly the Euro, British Pound, Australian Dollar and Canadian Dollar. Collectively, these currencies represent approximately 70% of the Company&#146;s operating income
outside the U.S. If all four of these currencies moved by 10% in the same direction compared with 2008, the Company&#146;s annual net income per share would change by about 12 to 15 cents. Due to the recent strengthening of the U.S.&nbsp;Dollar
relative to virtually all foreign currencies, full year 2009 revenues and operating income will likely be negatively impacted by foreign currency translation. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P
STYLE="font-size:4px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">The Company expects the effective income tax rate for the full-year 2009 to be approximately 29% to 31%. In the normal course of business and based on the timing of certain
transactions and events, some volatility may be experienced between the quarters resulting in a quarterly tax rate that is outside the annual range. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:4px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">The Company expects capital expenditures for 2009 to be approximately $2.1 billion. About half of this amount will be reinvested in existing restaurants while the rest will
primarily be used to open about 1,000 restaurants (950 traditional and 50 satellites). The Company expects net additions of about 650 restaurants (750 net traditional additions and 100 net satellite closings). These restaurant numbers include new
unit openings (approximately 30%) in affiliated and developmental licensed markets, such as Japan and Latin America, where the Company does not fund any capital expenditures. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P
STYLE="font-size:4px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">For 2007 through 2009, the Company expects to return $15&nbsp;billion to $17 billion to shareholders through share repurchases and dividends, subject to business and market
conditions. For 2007 and 2008 combined, the Company returned $11.5 billion to shareholders. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:4px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">The Company continually reviews its restaurant ownership structures to optimize cash flow and returns and to enhance local relevance. The Company expects to refranchise 1,000
to 1,500 Company-operated restaurants between 2008 and 2010, primarily in its major markets, and by continuing to utilize its developmental license strategy. In 2008, the Company refranchised about 675 restaurants, primarily in its major markets.
</FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:4px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">In February 2009, consistent with its focus on the McDonald&#146;s restaurant business, McDonald&#146;s agreed to sell its minority interest in Redbox Automated Retail, LLC,
an automated DVD rental service. The Company expects to recognize a nonoperating gain upon the closing of the transaction in first quarter 2009. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE></DIV><br clear="All"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT

<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px dotted #000000"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" ALIGN="right" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px dotted #000000"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="right"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="1"><B><I>Increase/</I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:1px"

</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:2px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="1"><I>nm Not meaningful. </I></FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:11px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P><DIV
STYLE="position:relative;float:left; margin-right:1%; width:48%;padding-right:9px;padding-bottom:8px;overflow:hidden"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">In August 2007, the Company completed the sale of its
businesses in Brazil, Argentina, Mexico, Puerto Rico, Venezuela and 13&nbsp;other countries in Latin America and the Caribbean, which totaled 1,571 restaurants, to a developmental licensee organization. The Company refers to these markets as
&#147;Latam.&#148; As a result of the Latam transaction, the Company receives royalties in these markets instead of a combination of Company-operated sales and franchised rents and royalties. </FONT></P> <P
STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:19px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">Based on approval by the Company&#146;s Board of Directors on April&nbsp;17, 2007, the Company concluded Latam was &#147;held for sale&#148; as of that date in
accordance with the requirements of SFAS No.&nbsp;144, <I>Accounting for the Impairment or Disposal of Long-lived Assets. </I>As a result, the Company recorded an impairment charge of $1.7 billion in 2007, substantially all of which was noncash. The
charge included $896 million for the difference between the net book value of the Latam business and approximately $675 million in cash proceeds received. This loss in value was primarily due to a historically difficult economic environment coupled
with volatility experienced in many of the markets included in this transaction. The charges also included historical foreign currency translation losses of $769 million recorded in shareholders&#146; equity. </FONT></P></DIV><DIV
STYLE="position:relative;float:right; width:48%;padding-right:9px;padding-bottom:8px;overflow:hidden"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:19px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">The Company recorded a tax benefit of $62 million in
2007 in connection with this transaction. As a result of meeting the &#147;held for sale&#148; criteria, the Company ceased recording depreciation expense with respect to Latam effective April&nbsp;17, 2007. In connection with the sale, the Company
agreed to indemnify the buyers for certain tax and other claims, certain of which are reflected as liabilities on McDonald&#146;s Consolidated balance sheet, totaling $142 million at December&nbsp;31, 2008 and $179 million at December&nbsp;31, 2007.
The change in the balance was primarily due to foreign currency translation. The Company mitigates the currency impact to income through the use of forward foreign exchange agreements. </FONT></P> <P
STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:19px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">The buyers of the Company&#146;s operations in Latam entered into a 20-year master franchise agreement that requires the buyers, among other obligations to
(i)&nbsp;pay monthly royalties commencing at a rate of approximately 5% of gross sales of the restaurants in these markets, substantially consistent with market rates for similar license arrangements; (ii)&nbsp;commit to adding approximately 150 new
McDonald&#146;s restaurants by the end of 2010 and pay an initial fee for each new restaurant opened; and (iii)&nbsp;commit to specified annual capital expenditures for existing restaurants. </FONT></P></DIV><br clear="All"> <P
STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P>
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="1">16 </FONT></P>

STYLE="font-size:11px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="line-height:0px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:2px;border-bottom:0.5pt solid #000000">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="font-size:11px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P><DIV
STYLE="position:relative;float:left; margin-right:1%; width:48%;padding-right:9px;padding-bottom:8px;overflow:hidden"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2"><B>Net income and diluted net income per common share </B>
</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:2px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">In 2008, net income and diluted net income per common share were $4.3 billion and $3.76. Results benefited by a $109 million, or $0.09 per share, gain on the sale of
the Company&#146;s minority interest in Pret A Manger. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:19px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">In 2007, net income and diluted net income per common share were $2.4 billion and $1.98.
Income from continuing operations was $2.3 billion or $1.93 per share, which included $1.6 billion or $1.30 per share of net expense related to the Latam transaction. This reflects an impairment charge of $1.32 per share, partly offset by a $0.02
per share benefit due to eliminating depreciation on the assets in Latam in mid-April 2007 in accordance with accounting rules. In addition, 2007 results included a net tax benefit of $288&nbsp;million or $0.24 per share resulting from the
completion of an IRS examination of the Company&#146;s 2003-2004 U.S. federal income tax returns, partly offset by the impact of a tax law change </FONT></P></DIV><DIV
STYLE="position:relative;float:right; width:48%;padding-right:9px;padding-bottom:8px;overflow:hidden"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">
<FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">in Canada. Income from discontinued operations was $60 million or $0.05 per share. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:19px"><FONT
FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">In 2006, net income and diluted net income per common share were $3.5 billion and $2.83. Income from continuing operations was $2.9 billion or $2.29 per share, which included $134 million ($98 million after tax or $0.08 per
share) of impairment and other charges primarily related to strategic actions taken to enhance overall profitability and improve returns, as well as $0.01 per share of net incremental income tax expense primarily related to the impact of a tax law
change in Canada. Income from discontinued operations was $678 million or $0.54 per share. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:19px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">Refer to the Impairment and other charges, net and
Discontinued operations sections for further discussion. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:19px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">The Company repurchased 69.7&nbsp;million shares of its stock for $4.0 billion in 2008 and
77.1&nbsp;million shares for $3.9 billion in 2007, driving reductions of over 4% and 3% of total shares outstanding, respectively, net of stock option exercises. </FONT></P></DIV><br clear="All"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P>
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="right"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="1">17 </FONT></P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" COLOR="#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2"><B>Impact of foreign currency translation on reported results </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:2px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">While changing foreign currencies affect reported results, McDonald&#146;s mitigates exposures, where practical, by financing in local currencies, hedging certain foreign-denominated cash flows, and purchasing goods and
services in local currencies. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:3%"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">In 2008, foreign currency translation had a positive impact on consolidated operating results, driven by the stronger
Euro and most other currencies, partly offset by the weaker British Pound. However, in fourth quarter 2008, the U.S. Dollar strengthened significantly against nearly every foreign currency, reducing the full year foreign currency benefit. Due to
this strengthening, full year 2009 revenues and operating income will likely be negatively impacted by foreign currency translation. In 2007, foreign currency translation had a positive impact on consolidated operating results, primarily driven by
the stronger Euro, British Pound, Australian Dollar and Canadian Dollar. In 2006, consolidated operating results were positively impacted by the stronger Euro, Canadian Dollar and British Pound. </FONT></P> <P
STYLE="margin-top:11px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2"><I>Impact of foreign currency translation on reported results </I></FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:8px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P> <P
STYLE="line-height:0px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:2px;border-bottom:0.5pt solid #000000">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" WIDTH="100%" BORDER="0" ALIGN="center">

<TR>
<TD WIDTH="56%"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" WIDTH="2%"></TD>
<TD></TD>
<TD></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" WIDTH="3%"></TD>

</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:11px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2"><B>Revenues </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:2px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">The Company&#146;s
revenues consist of sales by Company-operated restaurants and fees from restaurants operated by franchisees. Revenues from conventional franchised restaurants include rent and royalties based on a percent of sales along with minimum rent payments,
and initial fees. Revenues from restaurants licensed to affiliates and developmental licensees include a royalty based on a percent of sales, and may include initial fees. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:3%"><FONT
FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">In both 2008 and 2007, consolidated revenue growth was driven by positive comparable sales as well as stronger foreign currencies. Revenue growth in both years was negatively impacted by the Latam transaction. Upon completion
of the Latam transaction in August&nbsp;2007, the Company receives royalties based on a percent of sales in these markets instead of a combination of Company-operated sales and franchised rents and royalties. Revenue growth in 2008 was also partly
offset by the impact of the refranchising strategy in certain of the Company&#146;s major markets, which resulted in a higher proportion of franchised restaurants compared with 2007. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:11px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
FACE="Arial" SIZE="2"><I>Revenues </I></FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:8px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="line-height:0px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:2px;border-bottom:0.5pt solid #000000">&nbsp;</P>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="1">18 </FONT></P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" COLOR="#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

<DIV STYLE="position:relative;float:left; margin-right:1%; width:48%;padding-right:9px;padding-bottom:8px;overflow:hidden"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:3%"><FONT FACE="Arial"
SIZE="2">In the U.S., the increases in revenues in 2008 and 2007 were primarily driven by our market-leading breakfast business and the ongoing appeal of new products, as well as continued focus on everyday value and convenience. New products
introduced in 2008 included Southern Style Chicken products, Iced Coffee and Sweet Tea, while new products introduced in 2007 included the Southwest Salad and an extended Snack Wrap line. In 2008, revenue growth was largely offset by the impact of
the refranchising strategy. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:3%"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">Europe&#146;s constant currency increase in revenues in 2008 and 2007 was primarily due to strong comparable sales in
Russia (which is entirely Company-operated), France and the U.K., as well as positive comparable sales in all other markets. These increases were partly offset by the impact of the refranchising strategy, primarily in the U.K. and Germany in 2008
and in the U.K. in 2007. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:3%"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">In APMEA, the constant currency increases in revenues in 2008 and 2007 were primarily driven by strong comparable sales in
Australia and China, as well as positive comparable sales throughout the segment. In addition, expansion in China contributed to the increases in both years. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:3%"><FONT FACE="Arial"
SIZE="2">In Other Countries&nbsp;&amp; Corporate, Company-operated sales declined in 2008 and 2007 while franchised revenues increased primarily as a result of the Latam transaction in August 2007. </FONT></P> <P
STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:3%"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">The following tables present Systemwide sales and comparable sales increases: </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:11px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial"

<TD COLSPAN="1" NOWRAP VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px dotted #000000"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2"><B>&nbsp;</B></FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px dotted #000000"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="right" COLSPAN="1" VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px dotted #000000"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">10.8</FONT></TD>
<TD COLSPAN="1" NOWRAP VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px dotted #000000"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px dotted #000000"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="right" COLSPAN="1" VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px dotted #000000"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">9.4</FONT></TD>
<TD COLSPAN="1" NOWRAP VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px dotted #000000"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">&nbsp;</FONT></TD></TR>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000"> <P STYLE="margin-left:2.00em; text-indent:-1.00em"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">Total</FONT></P></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="right" COLSPAN="1" VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2"><B>6.9</B></FONT></TD>
<TD COLSPAN="1" NOWRAP VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2"><B>%</B></FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="right" COLSPAN="1" VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">6.8</FONT></TD>
<TD COLSPAN="1" NOWRAP VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">%</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="right" COLSPAN="1" VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">5.7</FONT></TD>
<TD COLSPAN="1" NOWRAP VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">%</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:11px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2"><B>Restaurant Margins </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:2px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">The Company
continues to optimize its restaurant ownership mix, cash flow and returns through its refranchising strategy and expects the shift to a greater percentage of franchised restaurants to negatively impact consolidated revenues as Company-operated sales
shift to franchised sales, where we receive rent and/or royalties. In addition, the Company expects a decrease in Company-operated margin dollars and an increase in franchised margin dollars, while margin percentages will vary based on sales and
cost structures of refranchised restaurants.<B> </B> </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P></DIV><DIV
STYLE="position:relative;float:right; width:48%;padding-right:9px;padding-bottom:8px;overflow:hidden">
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2"><B><I>&#149;</I></B></FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2"><B><I>Franchised margins </I></B></FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:2px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">Franchised margin dollars represent
revenues from franchised restaurants less the Company&#146;s occupancy costs (rent and depreciation) associated with those sites. Franchised margin dollars represented about 65% of the combined restaurant margins in 2008, 2007 and 2006. Franchised
margin dollars increased $695&nbsp;million or 14% (11% in constant currencies) in 2008 and $601&nbsp;million or 14% (10% in constant currencies) in 2007. The August&nbsp;2007 Latam transaction contributed to the growth in franchised margin dollars
in both 2008 and 2007 and the refranchising strategy contributed to the growth in 2008. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:11px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2"><I>Franchised margins </I></FONT></P> <P
STYLE="font-size:8px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="line-height:0px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:2px;border-bottom:0.5pt solid #000000">&nbsp;</P>

<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000"> <P STYLE="margin-left:2.00em; text-indent:-1.00em"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">Total</FONT></P></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2"><B>&nbsp;</B></FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000" ALIGN="right"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2"><B>82.3</B></FONT></TD>
<TD NOWRAP VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2"><B>%</B></FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000" ALIGN="right"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">81.5</FONT></TD>
<TD NOWRAP VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">%</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000" ALIGN="right"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">80.7</FONT></TD>
<TD NOWRAP VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">%</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:11px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:3%"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">In the U.S. and APMEA, the franchised margin percent increases in 2008 and 2007 were primarily driven by
positive comparable sales. In 2008, the U.S. franchised margin percent was negatively impacted by the refranchising strategy. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:3%"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">Europe&#146;s
franchised margin percent increased in 2008 and 2007 primarily due to strong comparable sales in most markets, partly offset by the impact of the refranchising strategy. Higher rent expense and the cost of strategic brand and sales building
initiatives also negatively affected the franchised margin percent in 2008. The Company will continue to execute these strategies, which are designed to drive comparable guest count growth and long term profitability and are expected to negatively
impact the 2009 franchised margin percent. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:3%"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">In Other Countries&nbsp;&amp; Corporate, the franchised margin percent increased in 2008 and 2007 as a
result of the Latam transaction. The Company receives royalties based on a percent of sales in these markets. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:3%"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">The franchised margin percent in APMEA
and, beginning in 2008, Other Countries &amp; Corporate is higher relative to the U.S. and Europe due to a large proportion of developmental licensed and/or affiliated restaurants where we have royalty income with no corresponding occupancy costs.
</FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:11px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2"><B><I>&#149;</I></B></FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2"><B><I>Company-operated margins </I></B></FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:2px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">Company-operated margin dollars
represent sales by Company-operated restaurants less the operating costs of these restaurants. Company-operated margin dollars increased $39 million or 1% (decreased 1% in constant currencies) in 2008 and increased $372 million or 15% (10% in
constant currencies) in 2007. After the Latam transaction in August 2007, there are no Company-operated restaurants remaining in Latin America. Company-operated margin dollars were negatively impacted by this transaction in 2008 and 2007 and by the
refranchising strategy in </FONT>
</P></DIV><br clear="All"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P>
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="right"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="1">19 </FONT></P>

</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:11px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:3%"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">In the U.S., the Company-operated margin percent decreased in 2008 and 2007 due to cost pressures including
higher commodity and labor costs, partly offset by positive comparable sales. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:3%"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">Europe&#146;s Company-operated margin percent increased in 2008 and
2007 primarily due to strong comparable sales, partly offset by higher commodity and labor costs. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:3%"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">In APMEA, the Company-operated margin percent in
2008 and 2007 increased due to strong comparable sales in most markets. Both years were negatively impacted by higher labor costs and 2008 was also negatively impacted by higher commodity costs. </FONT></P> <P
STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:3%"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">In Other Countries&nbsp;&amp; Corporate, the Company-operated margin in 2007 benefited by about 100 basis points related to the discontinuation of depreciation on
the assets in Latam from mid-April through July 2007. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:11px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2"><B><I>&#149;</I></B></FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2"><B><I>Supplemental information regarding Company-operated restaurants </I></B></FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:2px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial"
SIZE="2">We continually review our restaurant ownership mix with a goal of improving local relevance, profits and returns. In most cases, franchising is the best way to achieve these goals, but as previously stated, Company-operated restaurants are
also important to our success. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:3%"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">We report results for Company-operated restaurants based on their sales, less costs directly incurred by that business
including occupancy costs. We report the results for franchised restaurants based on franchised revenues, less associated occupancy costs. For this reason and because we manage our business based on geographic segments and not on the basis of our
ownership structure, we do not specifically allocate selling, general&nbsp;&amp; administrative expenses and other operating (income) expenses to Company-operated or franchised restaurants. Other operating items that relate to the Company-operated
restaurants generally include gains on sales of restaurant businesses and write-offs of equipment and leasehold improvements. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:3%"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">We believe the
following information about Company-operated restaurants in our most significant markets provides an additional perspective on this business. Management responsible for our Company-operated restaurants in these markets analyzes the Company-operated
business on this basis to assess its performance. Management of the Company also considers this information when evaluating restaurant ownership mix, subject to other relevant considerations. </FONT></P></DIV><DIV
STYLE="position:relative;float:right; width:48%;padding-right:9px;padding-bottom:8px;overflow:hidden"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:3%"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">The following tables seek to illustrate the two components
of our Company-operated margins. The first of these relates exclusively to restaurant operations, which we refer to below as &#147;Store operating margin.&#148; The second relates to the value of our Brand and the real estate interest we retain for
which we charge rent and royalties. We refer to this component as &#147;Brand/real estate margin.&#148; Both Company-operated and conventional franchised restaurants are charged rent and royalties, although rent and royalties for Company-operated
restaurants are eliminated in consolidation. Rent and royalties for both restaurant ownership types are based on a percentage of sales, and the actual rent percentage varies depending on the level of McDonald&#146;s investment in the restaurant.
Royalty rates may also vary by market. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:3%"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">As shown in the following tables, in disaggregating the components of our Company-operated margins, certain
costs with&nbsp;respect to Company-operated restaurants are reflected in Brand/real estate margin. Those costs consist of rent payable by McDonald&#146;s to third parties on leased sites and depreciation for buildings and leasehold improvements and
constitute a portion of occupancy&nbsp;&amp; other operating expenses recorded on the Consolidated statement of income. Store operating margins reflect rent and royalty expenses, and those amounts are accounted for as income in calculating
Brand/real estate margin. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:3%"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">While we believe that the following information provides a perspective in evaluating our Company-operated business, it is
not intended as a measure of our operating performance or as an alternative to operating income or restaurant margins as reported by the Company in accordance with accounting principles generally accepted in the U.S. In particular, as noted above,
we do not allocate selling, general&nbsp;&amp; administrative expenses to our Company-operated business. However, we believe that a range of $40,000 to $50,000 per restaurant, on average, is a typical range of costs to support this business in the
U.S. The actual costs in markets outside the U.S. will vary depending on local circumstances and the organizational structure of the market. These costs reflect the indirect services we believe are necessary to provide the appropriate support of the
restaurant. </FONT></P></DIV><br clear="All"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P>
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="1">20 </FONT></P>

<TR>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="1"><I>(1)</I></FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="1"><I>Represents certain costs recorded as occupancy&nbsp;&amp; other operating expenses on the Consolidated statement of income &#150; rent payable by McDonald&#146;s to third parties on leased
sites and depreciation for buildings and leasehold improvements. This adjustment is made to reflect these occupancy costs in Brand/real estate margin. The relative percentage of sites that are owned versus leased varies by country.
</I></FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:4px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="1"><I>(2)</I></FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="1"><I>Reflects average Company&#150;operated rent and royalties (as a percentage of 2008 sales: U.S. &#150; 14.8% and Europe &#150; 19.3%). This adjustment is made to reflect expense in Store
operating margin and income in Brand/real estate margin. Countries within Europe have varying economic profiles and a wide range of rent and royalty rates as a percentage of sales. </I></FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> <P
STYLE="font-size:11px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="line-height:0px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:2px;border-bottom:0.5pt solid #000000">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:11px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial"
SIZE="2"><B>Selling, general &amp; administrative expenses </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:2px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">Consolidated selling, general &amp; administrative expenses were flat (decreased 1% in constant
currencies) in 2008 and increased 3% (flat in constant currencies) in 2007. The 2008 constant currency change benefited by 3 percentage points due to the 2007 Latam transaction. In 2008, expenses included costs related to the Beijing Summer Olympics
and the Company&#146;s biennial Worldwide Owner/Operator Convention. In 2007, higher employee-related costs were offset by a reduction in costs due to the Latam transaction. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:11px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial"
SIZE="2"><I>Selling, general &amp; administrative expenses </I></FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:11px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="line-height:0px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:2px;border-bottom:0.5pt solid #000000">&nbsp;</P>

<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="right" COLSPAN="1" VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2"><B></B><B>(1</B><B></B></FONT></TD>
<TD COLSPAN="1" NOWRAP VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2"><B></B><B>)</B><B>%</B></FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="right" COLSPAN="1" VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">&#151;</FONT></TD>
<TD COLSPAN="1" NOWRAP VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">%</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="1"><I>(1)</I></FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="1"><I>Included in Other Countries &amp; Corporate are home office support costs in areas such as facilities, finance, human resources, information technology, legal, marketing, restaurant
operations, supply chain and training. </I></FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:11px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:3%"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">Selling, general &amp; administrative expenses as a percent of revenues were 10.0% in 2008
compared with 10.4% in 2007 and 11.0% in 2006. Selling, general &amp; administrative expenses as a percent of Systemwide sales were 3.3% in 2008 compared with 3.7% in 2007 and 4.0% in 2006. Management believes that analyzing selling, general &amp;
administrative expenses as a percent of Systemwide sales, as well as revenues, is meaningful because these costs are incurred to support Systemwide restaurants. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P>

impairment and other charges, net of $6 million in 2008, $1.7 billion in 2007 and $134 million in 2006. McDonald&#146;s management does not include these items when reviewing business performance trends because we do not believe these items are
indicative of expected ongoing results. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:11px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2"><I>Impairment and other charges (credits), net </I></FONT></P> <P

STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:3%"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">In 2006, the charges primarily related to losses of $36 million incurred on the transfers of the Company&#146;s ownership interest in certain markets, primarily in
APMEA and Europe, to developmental licensees, costs of $35 million related to the closing of certain restaurants in the U.K. in conjunction with an overall restaurant portfolio review, costs of $29 million to buy out certain litigating franchisees
in Brazil, asset write-offs and other charges in APMEA of $18 million, and a loss of $13 million related to the decision to dispose of supply chain operations in Russia. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:11px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial"

<TD WIDTH="11" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2"><B><I>&#149;</I></B></FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2"><B><I>Gains on sales of restaurant businesses </I></B></FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:2px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">Gains on sales of
restaurant businesses include gains from sales of Company-operated restaurants as well as gains from exercises of purchase options by franchisees with business facilities lease arrangements (arrangements where the Company leases the businesses,
including equipment, to franchisees who generally have options to purchase the businesses). The Company&#146;s purchases and sales of businesses with its franchisees are aimed at achieving an optimal ownership mix in each market. Resulting gains or
losses are recorded in operating income because the transactions are a recurring part of our business. The Company realized higher gains on sales of restaurant businesses in 2008 and 2007 primarily as a result of selling more Company-operated
restaurants in connection with our refranchising strategy in the Company&#146;s major markets. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:11px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="11" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2"><B><I>&#149;</I></B></FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2"><B><I>Equity in earnings of unconsolidated affiliates </I></B></FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:2px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial"
SIZE="2">Unconsolidated affiliates and partnerships are businesses in which the Company actively participates but does not control. The Company records equity in earnings from these entities representing </FONT></P></DIV><DIV
STYLE="position:relative;float:right; width:48%;padding-right:9px;padding-bottom:8px;overflow:hidden"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">
<FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">McDonald&#146;s share of results. For foreign affiliated markets &#150; primarily Japan &#150; results are reported after interest expense and income taxes.
McDonald&#146;s share of results for partnerships in certain consolidated markets such as the U.S. are reported before income taxes. These partnership restaurants are operated under conventional franchise arrangements and are included in
conventional franchised restaurant counts. Results in 2008 and 2007 reflected improved results from our Japanese affiliate. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:11px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="11" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2"><B><I>&#149;</I></B></FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2"><B><I>Asset dispositions and other expense </I></B></FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:2px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">Asset dispositions
and other expense consists of gains or losses on excess property and other asset dispositions, provisions for store closings, contingencies and uncollectible receivables, and other miscellaneous expenses. Asset dispositions in 2008 reflected lower
losses on restaurant closings and property disposals compared with 2007. In addition, 2008 results included income of $18 million due to the partial recovery of prior years&#146; sales taxes in the U.K. Results for 2006 reflected a gain of $26
million related to the sale of an office building in Russia. </FONT></P></DIV><br clear="All"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P>
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="1">22 </FONT></P>

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="1"><I>Results for 2007 included the impact of the Latam transaction in Other Countries&nbsp;&amp; Corporate. This impact reflects an impairment charge of $1,665 million, partly offset by a
benefit of $24 million due to eliminating depreciation on the assets in Latam in mid-April 2007. In order to provide management&#146;s view of the underlying business performance, results are also shown excluding the impact of the Latam transaction.
</I></FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:11px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P><DIV STYLE="position:relative;float:left; margin-right:1%; width:48%;padding-right:9px;padding-bottom:8px;overflow:hidden"> <P
STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">In the U.S., 2008 and 2007 results increased primarily due to higher franchised margin dollars. In 2007, operating income also included higher Company-operated restaurant margin
dollars compared with 2006. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:19px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">In Europe, results for 2008 and 2007 were driven by strong performance in France, Russia and the U.K. as well as
positive results in Germany and most other markets. Impairment and other charges, net in 2006 benefited the growth rate in 2007. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:19px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">In APMEA, results
for 2008 were driven by strong results in Australia and China, and positive performance in most other markets. Results for 2007 were driven by improved results in China, Japan, Australia, Hong Kong and most other markets. </FONT></P> <P
STYLE="font-size:11px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2"><B><I>Combined operating margin </I></B></FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:2px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">Combined operating margin is
defined as operating income as a percent of total revenues. Combined operating margin for 2008, 2007 and 2006 was 27.4%, 17.0% and 21.2%, respectively. Impairment and other charges negatively impacted the 2007 and 2006 combined operating margin by
7.4 percentage points and 0.7 percentage points, respectively. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:11px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2"><B>Interest expense </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:2px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial"
SIZE="2">Interest expense for 2008 increased primarily due to higher average debt levels, and to a lesser extent, higher average interest rates. Interest expense for 2007 increased primarily due to higher average interest rates and stronger foreign
currencies, partly offset by lower average debt levels. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:11px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2"><B>Nonoperating (income) expense, net </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:2px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT

</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:11px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">Interest income consists primarily of interest earned on short-term cash investments. Translation and hedging activity
primarily relates to net gains or losses on certain hedges that reduce the exposure to variability on certain intercompany foreign cash flow streams. Other expense primarily consists of gains or losses on early extinguishment of debt and minority
interest. </FONT></P></DIV><DIV STYLE="position:relative;float:right; width:48%;padding-right:9px;padding-bottom:8px;overflow:hidden"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:19px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">Interest income
decreased for 2008 primarily due to lower average interest rates and average cash balances, while 2007 decreased primarily due to lower average cash balances. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:11px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial"
SIZE="2"><B>Gain on Sale of Investment </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:2px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">In second quarter 2008, the Company sold its minority ownership interest in U.K.-based Pret A Manger. In connection with
the sale, the Company received cash proceeds of $229 million and recognized a nonoperating pretax gain of $160 million ($109 million after tax). </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:11px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2"><B>Provision for
income taxes </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:2px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">In 2008, 2007 and 2006, the reported effective income tax rates were 30.0%, 34.6%, and 31.0%, respectively. </FONT></P> <P
STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:19px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">In 2007, the effective income tax rate was impacted by about 4 percentage points as a result of the following items: </FONT></P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="11" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">A negative impact due to a minimal tax benefit of $62 million related to the Latam impairment charge of $1,641 million. This benefit was minimal due to the Company&#146;s
inability to utilize most of the capital losses generated by this transaction in 2007. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="11" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">A positive impact due to a benefit of $316 million resulting from the completion of an IRS examination, partly offset by $28 million of expense related to the impact of a tax
law change in Canada. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:8px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:19px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">Consolidated net deferred tax liabilities included tax assets, net of valuation allowance, of $1.4 billion
in 2008 and 2007. Substantially all of the net tax assets arose in the U.S. and other profitable markets. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:11px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2"><B>Discontinued operations </B></FONT></P> <P
STYLE="margin-top:2px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">The Company continues to focus its management and financial resources on the McDonald&#146;s restaurant business as it believes the opportunities for long-term growth remain
significant. Accordingly, during third quarter 2007, the Company sold its investment in Boston Market. In 2006, the Company disposed of its investment in Chipotle via public stock offerings in the first and second quarters and a tax-free exchange
for McDonald&#146;s common stock in the fourth quarter. As a result of the disposals during 2007 and 2006, both Boston Market&#146;s and Chipotle&#146;s results of operations and transaction gains are reflected as discontinued operations for all
periods presented. </FONT></P></DIV><br clear="All"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P>
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="right"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="1">23 </FONT></P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" COLOR="#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

<DIV STYLE="position:relative;float:left; margin-right:1%; width:48%;padding-right:9px;padding-bottom:8px;overflow:hidden"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:3%">
<FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">In connection with the Company&#146;s sale of its investment in Boston Market in August 2007, the Company received proceeds of approximately $250 million and recorded
a gain of $69 million after tax. In addition, Boston Market&#146;s net income (loss) for 2007 and 2006 was ($9) million and $7 million, respectively. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:3%"><FONT FACE="Arial"
SIZE="2">In first quarter 2006, Chipotle completed an IPO of 6.1&nbsp;million shares resulting in a tax-free gain to McDonald&#146;s of $32 million to reflect an increase in the carrying value of the Company&#146;s investment as a result of Chipotle
selling shares in the public offering. Concurrent with the IPO, McDonald&#146;s sold 3.0&nbsp;million Chipotle shares, resulting in net proceeds to the Company of $61 million and an additional gain of $14 million after tax. In second quarter 2006,
McDonald&#146;s sold an additional 4.5&nbsp;million Chipotle shares, resulting in net proceeds to the Company of $267 million and a gain of $128 million after tax, while still retaining majority ownership. In fourth quarter 2006, the Company
completely separated from Chipotle through a noncash, tax-free exchange of its remaining Chipotle shares for its common stock. McDonald&#146;s accepted 18.6&nbsp;million shares of its common stock in exchange for the 16.5&nbsp;million shares of
Chipotle class B common stock held by McDonald&#146;s and recorded a tax-free gain of $480 million. Chipotle&#146;s net income for 2006 was $18 million. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:11px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial"
SIZE="2"><B>Accounting changes </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:2px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2"><B><I>&#149;</I></B></FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2"><B><I>SFAS Statement No.&nbsp;158 </I></B></FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:2px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">In 2006, the Financial
Accounting Standards Board (FASB) issued Statement of Financial Accounting Standards No.&nbsp;158, <I>Employers&#146; Accounting for Defined Benefit Pension and Other Postretirement Plans</I>, <I>an amendment of FASB Statements No.&nbsp;87, 88, 106
and 132(R) </I>(SFAS No.&nbsp;158). SFAS No.&nbsp;158 requires the Company to recognize the overfunded or underfunded status of a defined benefit postretirement plan as an asset or liability on the Consolidated balance sheet and to recognize changes
in that funded status in the year changes occur through accumulated other comprehensive income. The Company adopted the applicable provisions of SFAS No.&nbsp;158 effective December&nbsp;31, 2006, as required. This resulted in a net decrease to
accumulated other comprehensive income of $89 million, for a limited number of applicable international markets. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:11px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2"><B><I>&#149;</I></B></FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2"><B><I>EITF Issue 06-2 </I></B></FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:2px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">In 2006, the FASB ratified Emerging Issues
Task Force (EITF) Issue 06-2, <I>Accounting for Sabbatical Leave and Other Similar Benefits Pursuant to FASB Statement No.&nbsp;43, Accounting for Compensated Absences </I>(EITF 06-2). Under EITF 06-2, compensation costs associated with a sabbatical
should be accrued over the requisite service period, assuming certain conditions are met. Previously, the Company expensed sabbatical costs as incurred. The Company adopted EITF 06-2 effective January&nbsp;1, 2007, as required and accordingly,
recorded a $36 million cumulative adjustment, net of tax, to decrease the January&nbsp;1,&nbsp;2007 balance of retained earnings. The annual impact to earnings is not significant. </FONT></P> <P
STYLE="font-size:11px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2"><B><I>&#149;</I></B></FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2"><B><I>FASB Interpretation No.&nbsp;48 </I></B></FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:2px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">In 2006, the FASB issued
Interpretation No.&nbsp;48, <I>Accounting for Uncertainty in Income Taxes </I>(FIN 48), which is an interpretation of FASB Statement No.&nbsp;109, <I>Accounting for Income Taxes</I>. FIN 48 clarifies the accounting for income taxes by prescribing
the minimum recognition threshold a tax position is required to meet before being recognized in the financial statements. FIN 48 also </FONT></P></DIV><DIV
STYLE="position:relative;float:right; width:48%;padding-right:9px;padding-bottom:8px;overflow:hidden"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">
<FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">provides guidance on derecognition, measurement, classification, interest and penalties, accounting in interim periods, disclosure and transition. The Company adopted
the provisions of FIN 48 effective January&nbsp;1, 2007, as required. As a result of the implementation of FIN 48, the Company recorded a $20 million cumulative adjustment to increase the January&nbsp;1, 2007 balance of retained earnings. FIN 48
requires that a liability associated with an unrecognized tax benefit be classified as a long-term liability except for the amount for which cash payment is anticipated within one year. Upon adoption of FIN 48, $339 million of tax liabilities, net
of deposits, were reclassified from current to long-term and included in other long-term liabilities. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:11px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2"><B><I>&#149;</I></B></FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2"><B><I>SFAS Statement No.&nbsp;157 </I></B></FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:2px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">In 2006, the FASB issued
Statement of Financial Accounting Standards No.&nbsp;157, <I>Fair Value Measurements </I>(SFAS No.&nbsp;157). SFAS No.&nbsp;157 defines fair value, establishes a framework for measuring fair value, and expands disclosures about fair value
measurements. This statement does not require any new fair value measurements; rather, it applies to other accounting pronouncements that require or permit fair value measurements. The provisions of SFAS No.&nbsp;157, as issued, were effective
January&nbsp;1,&nbsp;2008. However, in February 2008, the FASB issued FASB Staff Position No. FAS 157-2, <I>Effective Date of FASB Statement No.&nbsp;157</I>, which allows entities to defer the effective date of SFAS No.&nbsp;157, for one year, for
certain non-financial assets and non-financial liabilities, except those that are recognized or disclosed at fair value in the financial statements on a recurring basis (i.e., at least annually). The Company adopted SFAS No.&nbsp;157 as of
January&nbsp;1, 2008 and elected the deferral for non-financial assets and liabilities. The effect of adopting this standard was not significant, and we do not expect the January&nbsp;1, 2009 adoption of SFAS No.&nbsp;157 for non-financial assets
and liabilities to have a significant impact on our consolidated financial statements. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:11px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2"><B><I>&#149;</I></B></FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2"><B><I>SFAS Statement No.&nbsp;141(R) </I></B></FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:2px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">In 2007, the FASB issued
Statement of Financial Accounting Standards No.&nbsp;141(R), <I>Business Combinations </I>(SFAS No.&nbsp;141(R)). SFAS No.&nbsp;141(R) requires the acquiring entity in a business combination to record all assets acquired and liabilities assumed at
their respective acquisition-date fair values, changes the recognition of assets acquired and liabilities assumed arising from preacquisition contingencies, and requires the expensing of acquisition-related costs as incurred. SFAS No.&nbsp;141(R)
applies prospectively to business combinations for which the acquisition date is on or after January&nbsp;1, 2009. We do not expect the adoption of SFAS No.&nbsp;141(R) to have a significant impact on our consolidated financial statements.
</FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:11px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2"><B><I>SFAS Statement No.&nbsp;160 </I></B></FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:2px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">In 2007, the FASB issued
Statement of Financial Accounting Standards No.&nbsp;160, <I>Noncontrolling Interests in Consolidated Financial Statements </I>(an amendment of Accounting Research Bulletin No.&nbsp;51 (ARB 51)) (SFAS No.&nbsp;160). SFAS No.&nbsp;160 amends ARB 51
to establish accounting and reporting standards for the noncontrolling interest in a subsidiary and for the deconsolidation of a subsidiary. SFAS No.&nbsp;160 becomes effective beginning January&nbsp;1,&nbsp;2009 and is required to be adopted
prospectively, except for the reclassification of noncontrolling interests to equity and the recasting of net income (loss) attributable to both the controlling and noncontrolling interests, which are required to be </FONT>
