<TR>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="1"><I>(1)</I></FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="1"><I>APMEA represents Asia/Pacific, Middle East and Africa. </I></FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:4px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="1"><I>(2)</I></FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="1"><I>Other Countries&nbsp;&amp; Corporate represents Canada, Latin America and Corporate. </I></FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:11px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P><DIV
STYLE="position:relative;float:left; margin-right:1%; width:48%;padding-right:9px;padding-bottom:8px;overflow:hidden"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2"><B>Long-lived assets </B></FONT></P> <P
STYLE="margin-top:2px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">In accordance with Statement of Financial Accounting Standards No.&nbsp;144, <I>Accounting for the Impairment or Disposal of Long-Lived Assets </I>(SFAS No.&nbsp;144), long-lived
assets are reviewed for impairment annually in the fourth quarter and whenever events or changes in circumstances indicate that the carrying amount of an asset may not be recoverable. For purposes of annually reviewing McDonald&#146;s restaurant
assets for potential impairment, assets are initially grouped together at a television market level in the U.S. and at a country level for each of the international markets. The Company manages its restaurants as a group or portfolio with
significant common costs and promotional activities; as such, an individual restaurant&#146;s cash flows are not generally independent of the cash flows of others in a market. If an indicator of impairment (e.g., negative operating cash flows for
the most recent trailing 24-month period) exists for any grouping of assets, an estimate of undiscounted future cash flows produced by each individual restaurant within the asset grouping is compared to its carrying value. If an individual
restaurant is determined to be impaired, the loss is measured by the excess of the carrying amount of the restaurant over its fair value as determined by an estimate of discounted future cash flows. </FONT></P> <P
STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:19px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">Losses on assets held for disposal are recognized when management and the Board of Directors, as required, have approved and committed to a plan to dispose of the
assets, the assets are available for disposal, the disposal is probable of occurring within 12 months, and the net sales proceeds are expected to be less than its net book value, among other factors. Generally, such losses relate to restaurants that
have closed and ceased operations as well as other assets that meet the criteria to be considered &#147;available for sale&#148; in accordance with SFAS No.&nbsp;144. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P></DIV><DIV STYLE="position:relative;float:right; width:48%;padding-right:9px;padding-bottom:8px;overflow:hidden"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:19px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">When the Company
sells an existing business to a developmental licensee, the licensee purchases the business, including the real estate, and uses his/her capital and local knowledge to build the McDonald&#146;s Brand and optimize sales and profitability over the
long term. The sale of the business includes primarily land, buildings and improvements, and equipment, along with the franchising and leasing rights under existing agreements. Under the related developmental licensing arrangement, the Company
collects a royalty based on a percent of sales, as well as initial fees, but does not have either any capital invested in the business or any commitment to invest future capital. </FONT></P> <P
STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:19px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">An impairment charge is recognized for the difference between the net book value of the business (including any foreign currency translation adjustments recorded
in accumulated other comprehensive income in shareholders&#146; equity) and the estimated cash sales price, less costs of disposal. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:19px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">The Company
bases its accounting policy on management&#146;s determination that royalties payable under its developmental license arrangements are substantially consistent with market rates for similar license arrangements. Therefore, the Company believes that
the recognition of an impairment charge based on the net cash sales price reflects the substance of the sale transaction. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:11px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2"><B>Financial instruments </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:2px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">The Company generally borrows on a long-term basis and is exposed to the impact of interest rate changes and foreign currency fluctuations. The Company uses foreign currency
denominated debt and derivative instruments to mitigate the impact of these changes. The Company does not use derivatives with a level of complexity or with a risk higher than the exposures to be </FONT></P></DIV><br clear="All"> <P
STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P>
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="right"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="1">37 </FONT></P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" COLOR="#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

<DIV STYLE="position:relative;float:left; margin-right:1%; width:48%;padding-right:9px;padding-bottom:8px;overflow:hidden"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">
<FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">hedged and does not hold or issue derivatives for trading purposes. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:3%"><FONT FACE="Arial"
SIZE="2">The counterparties to these agreements consist of a diverse group of financial institutions. The Company continually monitors its positions and the credit ratings of its counterparties and adjusts positions as appropriate. The Company did
not have significant exposure to any individual counterparty at December&nbsp;31, 2008 and has master agreements that contain netting arrangements. Some of these agreements also require each party to post collateral if credit ratings fall below, or
aggregate exposures exceed, certain contractual limits. At December&nbsp;31, 2008, neither the Company nor its counterparties were required to post collateral on any derivative position. At December&nbsp;31, 2007, the Company was required to post
collateral of $54.8 million, which was used to reduce the carrying value of the derivatives recorded in other long-term liabilities. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:3%"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">Statement of
Financial Accounting Standards No.&nbsp;133, <I>Accounting for Derivative Instruments and Hedging Activities </I>(SFAS No.&nbsp;133), as amended, requires companies to recognize all derivatives as either assets or liabilities on the balance sheet at
fair value. SFAS No.&nbsp;133 also requires companies to designate all derivatives that qualify as hedging instruments as fair value hedges, cash flow hedges or hedges of net investments in foreign operations. This designation is based upon the
exposure being hedged. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:3%"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">The Company&#146;s use of derivatives primarily consists of interest rate exchange agreements, forward foreign currency
exchange agreements and foreign currency options. These derivatives were classified on the Consolidated balance sheet at December&nbsp;31, 2008 as follows: miscellaneous other assets&#150;$87.6 million; prepaid expenses and other current
assets&#150;$43.8 million; accrued payroll and other liabilities&#150;$22.1 million; and other long-term liabilities (excluding accrued interest)&#150;$3.5 million. For the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2007, the Company&#146;s derivatives were
recorded in miscellaneous other assets&#150;$63.7 million and other long-term liabilities (excluding accrued interest)&#150;$70.3 million. All derivative purchases and settlements are classified in other financing activities on the Consolidated
statement of cash flows. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:3%"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">There was no significant impact to the Company&#146;s earnings related to the ineffective portion of any hedging instruments
for the three years ended December&nbsp;31, 2008. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:11px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2"><B><I>&#149;</I></B></FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2"><B><I>Fair value hedges </I></B></FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:2px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">The Company enters into fair value
hedges to reduce the exposure to changes in the fair values of certain liabilities. The fair value hedges the Company enters into consist of&nbsp;interest rate exchange agreements which convert a portion of its fixed-rate debt into floating-rate
debt. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:3%"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">For fair value hedges, the gains or losses on derivatives as well as the offsetting gains or losses on the related hedged items resulting from
changes in fair value are recognized in nonoperating (income) expense, net. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:11px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2"><B><I>&#149;</I></B></FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2"><B><I>Cash flow hedges </I></B></FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:2px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">The Company enters into cash flow hedges
to reduce the exposure to variability in certain expected future cash flows. The types of cash flow hedges the Company enters into include (i)&nbsp;interest rate exchange agreements that effectively convert a portion of floating-rate debt to
fixed-rate debt and are designed to reduce the impact of interest rate changes on future interest expense; and (ii)&nbsp;forward foreign exchange contracts and foreign currency options that are designed to protect against the reduction in value of
forecasted foreign currency cash flows (such as royalties denominated in foreign currencies) due to changes in foreign currency exchange rates. </FONT></P></DIV><DIV
STYLE="position:relative;float:right; width:48%;padding-right:9px;padding-bottom:8px;overflow:hidden"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:3%"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">For cash flow hedges, the effective portion of the gains
or losses on derivatives is reported in the deferred hedging adjustment component of accumulated other comprehensive income in shareholders&#146; equity and reclassified into earnings in the same period or periods in which the hedged transaction
affects earnings. The remaining gain or loss, if any, is recognized in earnings currently. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:3%"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">The Company recorded after-tax adjustments related to cash
flow hedges to the deferred hedging adjustment component of accumulated other comprehensive income in shareholders&#146; equity. The Company recorded net increases of $47.3 million, $8.5 million and $10.7 million for the years ended
December&nbsp;31, 2008, 2007 and 2006, respectively. Based on interest rates and foreign currency exchange rates at December&nbsp;31, 2008, the majority of deferred hedging adjustments, after tax, included in accumulated other comprehensive income
in shareholders&#146; equity at December&nbsp;31, 2008, will be recognized in earnings in 2009 as the underlying hedged transactions are realized. The maximum maturity date of any cash flow hedge of forecasted transactions at December&nbsp;31, 2008
was 15 months, excluding an instrument hedging forecasted payments of variable interest on an existing financial instrument that matures in the fourth quarter of 2010. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:11px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2"><B><I>&#149;</I></B></FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2"><B><I>Hedges of net investments in foreign operations </I></B></FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:2px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">The
Company uses forward foreign exchange contracts and foreign currency denominated debt to hedge its investments in certain foreign subsidiaries and affiliates. Realized and unrealized translation adjustments from these hedges are included in
shareholders&#146; equity in the foreign currency translation component of accumulated other comprehensive income and offset translation adjustments on the underlying net assets of foreign subsidiaries and affiliates, which also are recorded in
accumulated other comprehensive income. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:3%"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">During the years ended December&nbsp;31, 2008, 2007 and 2006, the Company recorded decreases in translation
adjustments in accumulated other comprehensive income of $31.2 million after tax (included in the net decrease of $1.2 billion of translation adjustments on the Consolidated statement of shareholders&#146; equity), $76.5 million after tax, and $23.2
million after tax, respectively, related to hedges of net investments. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:11px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2"><B>Sales of stock by subsidiaries and affiliates </B></FONT></P> <P
STYLE="margin-top:2px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">As permitted by Staff Accounting Bulletin No.&nbsp;51 issued by the Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC), when a subsidiary or affiliate sells unissued shares in a public
offering, the Company records an adjustment to reflect an increase or decrease in the carrying value of its investment and a resulting nonoperating gain or loss. In 2006, the Company&#146;s gain of $32.0 million as a result of the Chipotle initial
public offering (IPO) is reported in discontinued operations. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:11px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2"><B>Income tax uncertainties </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:2px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">In 2006, the Financial Accounting Standards Board (FASB) issued Interpretation No.&nbsp;48, <I>Accounting for Uncertainty in Income Taxes </I>(FIN&nbsp;48), which is an interpretation of FASB Statement No.&nbsp;109,
<I>Accounting for Income Taxes. </I>FIN 48 clarifies the accounting for income taxes by prescribing the minimum recognition threshold a tax position is required to meet before being recognized in the financial statements. FIN 48 also provides
guidance on derecognition, measurement, classification, interest and penalties, accounting in interim periods, disclosure and transition. The Company adopted the </FONT>
</P></DIV><br clear="All"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P>
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="1">38 </FONT></P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" COLOR="#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

<DIV STYLE="position:relative;float:left; margin-right:1%; width:48%;padding-right:9px;padding-bottom:8px;overflow:hidden"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">
<FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">provisions of FIN 48 effective January&nbsp;1, 2007, as required. As a result of the implementation of FIN&nbsp;48, the Company recorded a $20.1 million cumulative
adjustment to increase the January&nbsp;1, 2007 balance of retained earnings. FIN&nbsp;48 requires that a liability associated with an unrecognized tax benefit be classified as a long-term liability except for the amount for which cash payment is
anticipated within one year. Upon adoption of FIN&nbsp;48, $338.7 million of net tax liabilities were reclassified from current to long-term. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:3%"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">The
Company, like other multi-national companies, is regularly audited by federal, state and foreign tax authorities, and tax assessments may arise several years after tax returns have been filed. Beginning in 2007, tax liabilities are recorded when, in
management&#146;s judgment, a tax position does not meet the more likely than not threshold for recognition as prescribed by FIN&nbsp;48. For tax positions that meet the more likely than not threshold, a tax liability may be recorded depending on
management&#146;s assessment of how the tax position will ultimately be settled. Prior to 2007, tax liabilities had been recorded when, in management&#146;s judgment, it was not probable that the Company&#146;s tax position would ultimately be
sustained. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:3%"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">The Company records interest on unrecognized tax benefits in the provision for income taxes. </FONT></P> <P
STYLE="margin-top:11px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2"><B>Per common share information </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:2px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">Diluted net income per common share is calculated using net
income divided by diluted weighted-average shares. Diluted weighted-average shares include weighted-average shares outstanding plus the dilutive effect of share-based compensation calculated using the treasury stock method, of (in millions of
shares): 2008&#150;19.4; 2007&#150;23.5; 2006&#150;17.7. Stock options that were not included in diluted weighted-average shares because they would have been antidilutive were (in millions of shares): 2008&#150;0.6; 2007&#150;0.7; 2006&#150;16.4.
</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:3%"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">The Company has elected to exclude the pro forma deferred tax asset associated with share-based compensation in net income per share. </FONT></P> <P
STYLE="margin-top:11px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2"><B>Statement of cash flows </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:2px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">The Company considers short-term, highly liquid investments with
an original maturity of 90 days or less to be cash equivalents. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:11px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2"><B>Employers&#146; accounting for defined benefit pension and other postretirement plans
</B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:2px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">In 2006, the FASB issued Statement of Financial Accounting Standards No.&nbsp;158, <I>Employers&#146; Accounting for Defined Benefit Pension and Other
Postretirement Plans, an amendment of FASB Statements No.&nbsp;87, 88, 106 and 132(R) </I>(SFAS No.&nbsp;158). SFAS No.&nbsp;158 requires the Company to recognize the overfunded or underfunded status of a defined benefit postretirement plan as an
asset or liability on the Consolidated balance sheet and to recognize changes in that funded status during the year through accumulated other comprehensive income. The Company adopted the applicable provisions of SFAS No.&nbsp;158 effective
December&nbsp;31, 2006, as required, which resulted in a net decrease to accumulated other comprehensive income of $89.0 million for a limited number of applicable international markets. In 2008, the Company recorded an unrecognized actuarial loss,
net of tax, of $60.4 million and in 2007 recorded an unrecognized actuarial gain, net of tax, of $51.3&nbsp;million, in accumulated other comprehensive income. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P></DIV><DIV STYLE="position:relative;float:right; width:48%;padding-right:9px;padding-bottom:8px;overflow:hidden"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2"><B>Sabbatical leave </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:2px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">In certain countries, eligible employees are entitled to take a paid sabbatical after a predetermined period of service. In 2006, the FASB ratified Emerging Issues Task Force
Issue 06-2, <I>Accounting for Sabbatical Leave and Other Similar Benefits Pursuant to FASB Statement No.&nbsp;43, Accounting for Compensated Absences </I>(EITF 06-2). Under EITF 06-2, compensation costs associated with a sabbatical should be accrued
over the requisite service period, assuming certain conditions are met. Previously, the Company expensed sabbatical costs as incurred. The Company adopted EITF 06-2 effective January&nbsp;1, 2007, as required and accordingly, recorded a $36.1
million cumulative adjustment, net of tax, to decrease beginning retained earnings in the first quarter 2007. The annual impact to earnings is not significant. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:11px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial"
SIZE="2"><B>Fair value measurements </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:2px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">In 2006, the FASB issued Statement of Financial Accounting Standards No.&nbsp;157, <I>Fair Value Measurements </I>(SFAS
No.&nbsp;157). SFAS No.&nbsp;157 defines fair value, establishes a framework for measuring fair value in accordance with generally accepted accounting principles, and expands disclosures about fair value measurements. This statement does not require
any new fair value measurements; rather, it applies to other accounting pronouncements that require or permit fair value measurements. The provisions of SFAS No.&nbsp;157, as issued, were effective January&nbsp;1, 2008. However, in February 2008,
the FASB deferred the effective date of SFAS No.&nbsp;157 for one year for certain non-financial assets and non-financial liabilities, except those that are recognized or disclosed at fair value in the financial statements on a recurring basis
(i.e., at least annually). The Company adopted the required provisions of SFAS No.&nbsp;157 related to debt and derivatives as of January&nbsp;1, 2008 and elected the deferral for non-financial assets and liabilities. The effect of adopting this
standard was not significant, and the Company does not expect the January&nbsp;1, 2009 adoption of SFAS No.&nbsp;157 for non-financial assets and liabilities to have a significant impact on its consolidated financial statements. </FONT></P> <P
STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:3%"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">Fair value is defined under SFAS No.&nbsp;157 as the price that would be received to sell an asset or paid to transfer a liability in the principal or most
advantageous market in an orderly transaction between market participants on the measurement date. SFAS No.&nbsp;157 also establishes a three-level hierarchy, which requires an entity to maximize the use of observable inputs and minimize the use of
unobservable inputs when measuring fair value. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:3%"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">The valuation hierarchy is based upon the transparency of inputs to the valuation of an asset or
liability on the measurement date. The three levels are defined as follows: </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:4px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">Level 1 &#150; inputs to the valuation methodology are quoted prices (unadjusted) for an identical asset or liability in an active market. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P
STYLE="font-size:4px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">Level 2 &#150; inputs to the valuation methodology include quoted prices for a similar asset or liability in an active market or model-derived valuations in which all
significant inputs are observable for substantially the full term of the asset or liability. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:4px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">&#149;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">Level 3 &#150; inputs to the valuation methodology are unobservable and significant to the fair value measurement of the asset or liability. </FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P
STYLE="margin-top:4px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:3%"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">The Company&#146;s use of derivatives primarily consists of interest rate exchange agreements, forward foreign currency exchange agreements and foreign currency
options. The Company does not </FONT>
</P></DIV><br clear="All"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P>
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="right"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="1">39 </FONT></P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" COLOR="#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

<DIV STYLE="position:relative;float:left; margin-right:1%; width:48%;padding-right:9px;padding-bottom:8px;overflow:hidden"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">
<FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">use derivatives with a level of complexity or with a risk higher than the exposures to be hedged and does not hold or issue derivatives for trading purposes.
</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:3%"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">Certain of the Company&#146;s derivatives are valued using various pricing models or discounted cash flow analyses that incorporate observable market
parameters, such as interest rate yield curves, option volatilities and currency rates, classified as Level 2 within the valuation hierarchy. In accordance with the requirements of SFAS No.&nbsp;157, derivative valuations incorporate credit risk
adjustments that are necessary to reflect the probability of default by the counterparty or the Company. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:3%"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">The following table presents financial
assets and liabilities measured at fair value on a recurring basis as of December&nbsp;31, 2008 by SFAS No.&nbsp;157 valuation hierarchy: </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:11px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P> <P

</I></FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:11px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2"><B>Business combinations </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:2px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">In 2007, the FASB issued
Statement of Financial Accounting Standards No.&nbsp;141(R), <I>Business Combinations </I>(SFAS No.&nbsp;141(R)). SFAS No.&nbsp;141(R) requires the acquiring entity in a business combination to record all assets acquired and liabilities assumed at
their respective acquisition-date fair values, changes the recognition of assets acquired and liabilities assumed arising from preacquisition contingencies, and requires the expensing of acquisition-related costs as incurred. SFAS No.&nbsp;141(R)
applies prospectively to business combinations for which the acquisition date is on or after January&nbsp;1, 2009. We do not expect the adoption of SFAS No.&nbsp;141(R) to have a significant impact on our consolidated financial statements.
</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:11px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2"><B>Noncontrolling interests </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:2px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">In 2007, the FASB issued Statement of Financial
Accounting Standards No.&nbsp;160, <I>Noncontrolling Interests in Consolidated Financial Statements </I>(an amendment of Accounting Research Bulletin No. 51 (ARB 51)) (SFAS No.&nbsp;160). SFAS No.&nbsp;160 amends ARB 51 to establish accounting and
reporting standards for the noncontrolling interest in a subsidiary and for the deconsolidation of a subsidiary. SFAS No.&nbsp;160 becomes effective beginning January&nbsp;1, 2009 and is required to be adopted prospectively, except for the
reclassification of noncontrolling interests to equity and the recasting of net income (loss) attributable to both the controlling and noncontrolling interests, which are required to be adopted retrospectively. We do not expect the adoption of SFAS
No.&nbsp;160 to have a significant impact on our consolidated financial statements. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P></DIV><DIV
STYLE="position:relative;float:right; width:48%;padding-right:9px;padding-bottom:8px;overflow:hidden"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2"><B>PROPERTY AND EQUIPMENT </B></FONT></P> <P
STYLE="font-size:8px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="line-height:0px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:2px;border-bottom:0.5pt solid #000000">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:2px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">Net
property and equipment consisted of: </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:11px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="line-height:0px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:2px;border-bottom:0.5pt solid #000000">&nbsp;</P>

2007-$1,145.0; 2006-$1,146.3. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:11px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2"><B>DISCONTINUED OPERATIONS </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:8px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P> <P
STYLE="line-height:0px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:2px;border-bottom:0.5pt solid #000000">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:2px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">The Company continues to focus its management and financial resources on
the McDonald&#146;s restaurant business as it believes the opportunities for long-term growth remain significant. Accordingly, during the third quarter 2007, the Company sold its investment in Boston Market. In 2006, the Company disposed of its
investment in Chipotle via public stock offerings in the first and second quarters and a tax-free exchange for McDonald&#146;s common stock in the fourth quarter. As a result of the disposals during 2007 and 2006, both Boston Market&#146;s and
Chipotle&#146;s results of operations and transaction gains are reflected as discontinued operations for all periods presented. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:3%"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">In connection with
the Company&#146;s sale of its investment in Boston Market in August 2007, the Company received proceeds of approximately $250 million and recorded a gain of $68.6 million after tax. In addition, Boston Market&#146;s net income (loss) for 2007 and
2006 was ($8.5) million and $6.9 million, respectively. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:3%"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">In first quarter 2006, Chipotle completed an IPO of 6.1&nbsp;million shares resulting in a
tax-free gain to McDonald&#146;s of $32.0 million to reflect an increase in the carrying value of the Company&#146;s investment as a result of Chipotle selling shares in the public offering. Concurrent with the IPO, McDonald&#146;s sold
3.0&nbsp;million Chipotle shares, resulting in net proceeds to the Company of $61.4 million and an additional gain of $13.6 million after tax. In second quarter 2006, McDonald&#146;s sold an additional 4.5&nbsp;million Chipotle shares, resulting in
net proceeds to the Company of $267.4 million and a gain of $127.8 million after tax, while still retaining majority ownership. In fourth quarter 2006, the Company completely separated from Chipotle through a noncash, tax-free exchange of its
remaining Chipotle shares for its common stock. McDonald&#146;s accepted 18.6&nbsp;million shares of its common stock in exchange for the 16.5&nbsp;million shares of Chipotle class B common stock held by McDonald&#146;s and recorded a tax-free gain
of $479.6 million. In addition, Chipotle&#146;s net income for 2006 was $18.2 million. </FONT></P></DIV><br clear="All"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P>

<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000" ALIGN="right"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">39.8</FONT></TD></TR>
</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:11px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2"><B>LATAM TRANSACTION </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:8px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P> <P
STYLE="line-height:0px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:2px;border-bottom:0.5pt solid #000000">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:2px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">In August 2007, the Company completed the sale of its businesses in Brazil,
Argentina, Mexico, Puerto Rico, Venezuela and 13 other countries in Latin America and the Caribbean, which totaled 1,571 restaurants, to a developmental licensee organization. The Company refers to these markets as &#147;Latam&#148;. Based on
approval by the Company&#146;s Board of Directors on April&nbsp;17, 2007, the Company concluded Latam was &#147;held for sale&#148; as of that date in accordance with the requirements of SFAS No.&nbsp;144. As a result, the Company recorded an
impairment charge of $1.7 billion in 2007, substantially all of which was noncash. The total charges for the full year included $895.8 million for the difference between the net book value of the Latam business and approximately $675&nbsp;million in
cash proceeds received. This loss in value was primarily due to a historically difficult economic environment coupled with volatility experienced in many of the markets included in this transaction. The charges also included historical foreign
currency translation losses of $769.5 million recorded in shareholders&#146; equity. The Company recorded a tax benefit of $62.0&nbsp;million in connection with this transaction. The tax benefit was minimal in 2007 due to the Company&#146;s
inability to utilize most of the capital losses generated by this transaction. As a result of meeting the &#147;held for sale&#148; criteria, the Company ceased recording depreciation expense with respect to Latam effective April&nbsp;17, 2007. In
connection with the sale, the Company agreed to indemnify the buyers for certain tax and other claims, certain of which are reflected in other long-term liabilities on McDonald&#146;s Consolidated balance sheet, totaling $141.8 million at
December&nbsp;31, 2008 and $179.2&nbsp;million at December&nbsp;31, 2007. The change in the balance was primarily due to foreign currency translation. The Company mitigates the currency impact to income through the use of forward foreign exchange
agreements. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:3%"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">The buyers of the Company&#146;s operations in Latam entered into a 20-year master franchise agreement that requires the buyers, among
other obligations to (i)&nbsp;pay monthly royalties commencing at a rate of approximately 5% of gross sales of the restaurants in these markets, substantially consistent with market rates for similar license arrangements; (ii)&nbsp;commit to adding
approximately 150 new McDonald&#146;s restaurants by the end of 2010 and pay an initial fee for each new restaurant opened; and (iii)&nbsp;commit to specified annual capital expenditures for existing restaurants. </FONT></P> <P
STYLE="margin-top:11px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2"><B>IMPAIRMENT AND OTHER CHARGES, NET </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:8px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P> <P
STYLE="line-height:0px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:2px;border-bottom:0.5pt solid #000000">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:2px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">On a pretax basis, the Company recorded impairment and other charges, net
of $6.0 million in 2008, $1,670.3 million in 2007 and $134.2 million in 2006. </FONT></P></DIV><DIV STYLE="position:relative;float:right; width:48%;padding-right:9px;padding-bottom:8px;overflow:hidden"> <P
STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:3%"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">In 2008, the charges primarily related to market restructuring costs in Greece. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:3%"><FONT
FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">In 2007, the Company recorded a charge of $1.7 billion related to the sale of the Latam businesses to a developmental licensee. In addition, the charges for 2007 included a $15.7 million write-off of assets associated with the
Toasted Deli Sandwich products in Canada and a net gain of $14.1 million as a result of the transfer of the Company&#146;s ownership interest in three European markets to a developmental licensee, partly offset by a loss on the transfer of a small
market in Europe to a developmental licensee. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:3%"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">In 2006, the charges primarily related to losses of $35.8 million incurred on the transfers of the
Company&#146;s ownership interest in certain markets, primarily in APMEA and Europe, to developmental licensees, costs of $35.3 million related to the closing of certain restaurants in the U.K. in conjunction with an overall restaurant portfolio
review, costs of $29.3&nbsp;million to buy out certain litigating franchisees in Brazil, asset write-offs and other charges in APMEA of $17.5&nbsp;million, and a loss of $13.1&nbsp;million related to the decision to dispose of supply chain
operations in Russia. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:11px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2"><B>OTHER OPERATING (INCOME) EXPENSE, NET </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:8px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P> <P
STYLE="line-height:0px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:2px;border-bottom:0.5pt solid #000000">&nbsp;</P>

<TR>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2"><B><I>&#149;</I></B></FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2"><B><I>Gains on sales of restaurant businesses </I></B></FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:2px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">Gains on sales of
restaurant businesses include gains from sales of Company-operated restaurants as well as gains from exercises of purchase options by franchisees with business facilities lease arrangements (arrangements where the Company leases the businesses,
including equipment, to franchisees who generally have options to purchase the businesses). The Company&#146;s purchases and sales of businesses with its franchisees are aimed at achieving an optimal ownership mix in each market. Resulting gains or
losses are recorded in operating income because the transactions are a recurring part of our business. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:11px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2"><B><I>&#149;</I></B></FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2"><B><I>Equity in earnings of unconsolidated affiliates </I></B></FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:2px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial"
SIZE="2">Unconsolidated affiliates and partnerships are businesses in which the Company actively participates but does not control. The Company records equity in earnings from these entities representing McDonald&#146;s share of results. For foreign
affiliated markets &#150; primarily Japan &#150; results are reported after interest expense and income taxes. McDonald&#146;s share of results for partnerships in certain consolidated markets such as the U.S. are reported before income taxes. These
partnership restaurants are operated under conventional franchise arrangements and are included in conventional franchised restaurant counts. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:11px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2"><B><I>&#149;</I></B></FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2"><B><I>Asset dispositions and other expense </I></B></FONT></P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:2px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">Asset dispositions
and other expense consists of gains or losses on excess property and other asset dispositions, provisions for store closings, contingencies and uncollectible receivables, and other miscellaneous income and expenses. </FONT></P></DIV><br clear="All">
<P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P>
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="right"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="1">41 </FONT></P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" COLOR="#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

<DIV STYLE="position:relative;float:left; margin-right:1%; width:48%;padding-right:9px;padding-bottom:8px;overflow:hidden"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2"><B>GAIN
ON SALE OF INVESTMENT </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:8px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="line-height:0px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:2px;border-bottom:0.5pt solid #000000">&nbsp;</P> <P
STYLE="margin-top:2px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">In second quarter 2008, the Company sold its minority ownership interest in U.K.-based Pret A Manger. In connection with the sale, the Company received cash proceeds of $229.4
million and recognized a nonoperating pretax gain of $160.1 million ($109.0 million after tax). </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:11px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2"><B>CONTINGENCIES </B></FONT></P> <P
STYLE="font-size:8px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="line-height:0px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:2px;border-bottom:0.5pt solid #000000">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:2px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">From
time to time, the Company is subject to proceedings, lawsuits and other claims related to competitors, customers, employees, franchisees, government agencies, intellectual property, shareholders and suppliers. The Company is required to assess the
likelihood of any adverse judgments or outcomes to these matters as well as potential ranges of probable losses. A determination of the amount of accrual required, if any, for these contingencies is made after careful analysis of each matter. The
required accrual may change in the future due to new developments in each matter or changes in approach such as a change in settlement strategy in dealing with these matters. The Company does not believe that any such matter currently being reviewed
will have a material adverse effect on its financial condition or results of operations. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:3%"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">In connection with the 2007 sale of the Company&#146;s
businesses in Latam, the Company agreed to indemnify the buyers for certain tax and other claims, certain of which are reflected as liabilities on McDonald&#146;s Consolidated balance sheet, totaling $141.8 million at December&nbsp;31, 2008 and
$179.2 million at December&nbsp;31, 2007. The change in the balance was primarily due to foreign currency translation. The Company mitigates the currency impact to income through the use of forward foreign exchange agreements. </FONT></P> <P
STYLE="margin-top:11px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2"><B>FRANCHISE ARRANGEMENTS </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:8px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P> <P
STYLE="line-height:0px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:2px;border-bottom:0.5pt solid #000000">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:2px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">Conventional franchise arrangements generally include a lease and a license
and provide for payment of initial fees, as well as continuing rent and royalties to the Company based upon a percent of sales with minimum rent payments that parallel the Company&#146;s underlying leases and escalations (on properties that are
leased). Under this arrangement, franchisees are granted the right to operate a restaurant using the McDonald&#146;s System and, in most cases, the use of a restaurant facility, generally for a period of 20 years. These franchisees pay related
occupancy costs including property taxes, insurance and maintenance. In addition, in certain markets outside the U.S., franchisees pay a refundable, non-interest bearing security deposit. Affiliates and developmental licensees operating under
license agreements pay a royalty to the Company based upon a percent of sales, and may pay initial fees. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:3%"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">The results of operations of restaurant
businesses purchased and sold in transactions with franchisees were not material to the consolidated financial statements for periods prior to purchase and sale. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:3%"><FONT
FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">Revenues from franchised restaurants consisted of: </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:11px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P> <P
STYLE="line-height:0px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:2px;border-bottom:0.5pt solid #000000">&nbsp;</P>

</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:6px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:3%"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">At December&nbsp;31, 2008, net property and equipment under franchise arrangements totaled $11.9 billion
(including land of $3.5 billion) after deducting accumulated depreciation and amortization of $5.7 billion. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:11px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2"><B>LEASING ARRANGEMENTS </B></FONT></P> <P
STYLE="font-size:8px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="line-height:0px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:2px;border-bottom:0.5pt solid #000000">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:2px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">At
December&nbsp;31, 2008, the Company was the lessee at 13,620 restaurant locations through ground leases (the Company leases the land and the Company or franchisee owns the building) and through improved leases (the Company leases land and
buildings). Lease terms for most restaurants are generally for 20 years and, in many cases, provide for rent escalations and renewal options, with certain leases providing purchase options. Escalation terms vary by geographic segment with examples
including fixed-rent escalations, escalations based on an inflation index, and fair-value market adjustments. The timing of these escalations generally ranges from annually to every five years. For most locations, the Company is obligated for the
related occupancy costs including property taxes, insurance and maintenance; however, for franchised sites, the Company requires the franchisees to pay these costs. In addition, the Company is the lessee under noncancelable leases covering certain
offices and vehicles. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:3%"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">Future minimum payments required under existing operating leases with initial terms of one year or more are: </FONT></P> <P

<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="1"><I>(1)</I></FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="1"><I>Included in other long-term liabilities on the Consolidated balance sheet. </I></FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:11px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:3%"><FONT FACE="Arial"
SIZE="2">It is reasonably possible that the total amount of unrecognized tax benefits could decrease within the next 12 months by $30&nbsp;million to $40 million. This decrease would result from the expiration of the statute of limitations and the
completion of tax audits in multiple tax jurisdictions. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:3%"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">The Company is generally no longer subject to U.S. federal, state and local, or non-U.S.
income tax examinations by tax authorities for years prior to 2002. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:3%"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">The continuing practice of the Company is to recognize interest and penalties
related to income tax matters in the provision for income taxes. The Company had $24.1 million and $9.4 million accrued for interest at December 31, 2008 and 2007, respectively, and no accrual for penalties in either year. The Company recorded
interest expense related to tax matters of $13.7&nbsp;million in 2008 and interest income related to tax matters of $34.9&nbsp;million in 2007, and no expense for penalties in either year. </FONT></P> <P
STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:3%"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">Deferred U.S. income taxes have not been recorded for temporary differences related to investments in certain foreign subsidiaries and corporate joint ventures.
These temporary differences were approximately $6.9 billion at December&nbsp;31, 2008 and consisted primarily of undistributed earnings considered permanently invested in operations outside the U.S. Determination of the deferred income tax liability
on these unremitted earnings is not practicable because such liability, if any, is dependent on circumstances existing if and when remittance occurs. </FONT></P></DIV><br clear="All"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;
</FONT></P>
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="right"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="1">43 </FONT></P>

<DIV STYLE="position:relative;float:left; margin-right:1%; width:48%;padding-right:9px;padding-bottom:8px;overflow:hidden"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial"
SIZE="2"><B>SEGMENT AND GEOGRAPHIC INFORMATION </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:8px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="line-height:0px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:2px;border-bottom:0.5pt solid #000000">&nbsp;</P> <P
STYLE="margin-top:2px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">The Company operates in the food service industry and manages its business as distinct geographic segments. </FONT></P> <P
STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:3%"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">All intercompany revenues and expenses are eliminated in computing revenues and operating income. Royalties and other payments from subsidiaries outside the U.S.
were (in millions): 2008&#150;$1,229.8; 2007&#150;$1,116.7; 2006&#150;$945.4. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:3%"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">Corporate general&nbsp;&amp; administrative expenses are included in
Other Countries&nbsp;&amp; Corporate and consist of home office support costs in areas such as facilities, finance, human resources, information technology, legal, marketing, restaurant operations, supply chain and training. Corporate assets include
corporate cash and equivalents, asset portions of financial instruments and home office facilities. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:11px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P> <P
STYLE="line-height:0px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:2px;border-bottom:0.5pt solid #000000">&nbsp;</P>

STYLE="font-size:4px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="1"><I>(1)</I></FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="1"><I>Includes $1.7 billion of charges/(credits) (Other Countries&nbsp;&amp; Corporate&#150;$1,681.0 million and Europe&#150;($10.7) million) primarily related to the Latam transaction. </I>
</FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P></DIV><DIV STYLE="position:relative;float:right; width:48%;padding-right:9px;padding-bottom:8px;overflow:hidden">
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="1"><I>(2)</I></FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="1"><I>Includes $134.2 million of charges (Europe&#150;$61.9 million; APMEA&#150;$48.2 million and Other Countries&nbsp;&amp; Corporate&#150;$24.1 million) primarily related to losses incurred on
the transfers of the Company&#146;s ownership interest in certain markets to developmental licensees and certain other strategic actions. </I></FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:11px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:3%"><FONT FACE="Arial"
SIZE="2">Total long-lived assets, primarily property and equipment, were (in millions)&#151;Consolidated: 2008&#150;$24,385.8; 2007&#150;$25,186.9; 2006&#150;$23,185.3. U.S. based: 2008&#150;$10,389.7; 2007&#150;$10,043.7; 2006&#150;$9,421.6.
</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:11px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2"><B>DEBT FINANCING </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:8px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P> <P
STYLE="line-height:0px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:2px;border-bottom:0.5pt solid #000000">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:2px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2"><B>Line of credit agreements </B></FONT></P> <P
STYLE="margin-top:2px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">At December&nbsp;31, 2008, the Company had a $1.3 billion line of credit agreement expiring in 2012 with fees of 0.05%&nbsp;per annum on the total commitment, which remained
unused. Fees and interest rates on this line are based on the Company&#146;s long-term credit rating assigned by Moody&#146;s and Standard&nbsp;&amp; Poor&#146;s. In addition, certain subsidiaries outside the U.S. had unused lines of credit totaling
$783.2 million at December&nbsp;31, 2008; these uncommitted lines of credit were principally short-term and denominated in various currencies at local market rates of interest. </FONT></P> <P
STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:3%"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">As a result of the Company&#146;s decision to repatriate certain foreign earnings under the Homeland Investment Act (HIA), certain wholly-owned subsidiaries outside
the U.S. entered into a multi-currency term loan facility totaling $2.9 billion in 2005. The facility expired in 2008, and the $1.8 billion in outstanding borrowings at December&nbsp;31, 2007 were repaid during 2008. </FONT></P> <P
STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:3%"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">The weighted-average interest rate of short-term borrowings was 4.7% at December&nbsp;31, 2008 (based on $232.1 million of commercial paper and $625.4 million of
foreign currency bank line borrowings) and 5.9% at December&nbsp;31, 2007 (based on $625.8&nbsp;million of foreign currency bank line borrowings). </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:11px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2"><B>Fair values
</B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:2px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">At December&nbsp;31, 2008, the fair value of the Company&#146;s debt obligations was estimated at $10.3 billion, compared to a carrying amount of $10.2 billion.
This fair value was estimated using various pricing models or discounted cash flow analyses that incorporated quoted market prices and are similar to Level 2 inputs within the SFAS No. 157 valuation hierarchy. The Company has no current plans to
retire a significant amount of its debt prior to maturity. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:3%"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">The carrying amounts for both cash and equivalents and notes receivable approximate fair
value. No fair value was estimated for non-interest bearing security deposits by franchisees, because these deposits are an integral part of the overall franchise arrangements. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:11px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT
FACE="Arial" SIZE="2"><B>Debt obligations </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:2px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">The Company has incurred debt obligations principally through public and private offerings and bank loans. There are no
provisions in the Company&#146;s debt obligations that would accelerate repayment of debt as a result of a change in credit ratings or a material adverse change in the Company&#146;s business. Certain of the Company&#146;s debt obligations contain
cross-acceleration provisions, and restrictions on Company and subsidiary mortgages and the long-term debt of certain subsidiaries. Under certain agreements, the Company has the option to retire debt prior to maturity, either at par or at a premium
over par. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:3%"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">In January 2009, the Company issued $400 million of 10-year U.S.&nbsp;Dollar-denominated notes at a coupon rate of 5.0%, and
$350&nbsp;million of 30-year U.S.&nbsp;Dollar-denominated bonds at a coupon rate of 5.7%. </FONT></P></DIV><br clear="All"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P>
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="1">44 </FONT></P>

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="1"><I>Aggregate maturities for 2008 debt balances, before fair value adjustments, were as follows (in millions): 2009&#150;$31.8; 2010&#150;$616.5; 2011&#150;$610.9; 2012&#150;$2,214.3;
2013&#150;$657.0; Thereafter&#150;$5,979.7. These amounts include a reclassification of short-term obligations totaling $1.3 billion to long-term obligations as they are supported by a long-term line of credit agreement expiring in 2012.

<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="1"><I>(4)</I></FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="1"><I>SFAS No.&nbsp;133 requires that the carrying value of underlying items in fair value hedges, in this case debt obligations, be adjusted for fair value changes to the extent they are
attributable to the risk designated as being hedged. The related hedging instrument is also recorded at fair value in either miscellaneous other assets or other long-term liabilities. A portion ($25.1&nbsp;million) of the adjustments at
December&nbsp;31, 2008 related to interest rate exchange agreements that were terminated in December 2002 and will amortize as a reduction of interest expense over the remaining life of the debt. </I></FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> <P
STYLE="font-size:4px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="1"><I>(5)</I></FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="1"><I>Includes notes payable, current maturities of long-term debt and long-term debt included on the Consolidated balance sheet. The increase in debt obligations from December&nbsp;31, 2007 to
December&nbsp;31, 2008 was due to (in millions): net issuances ($1,045.7), SFAS No.&nbsp;133 noncash fair value adjustments ($22.3) and other changes ($4.0), partly offset by changes in exchange rates on foreign currency denominated debt ($155.3).
</I></FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:10px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="font-size:10px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P><DIV
STYLE="position:relative;float:left; margin-right:1%; width:48%;padding-right:9px;padding-bottom:8px;overflow:hidden"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2"><B>ESOP loans </B></FONT></P> <P
STYLE="margin-top:2px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">Borrowings related to the leveraged Employee Stock Ownership Plan (ESOP) at December&nbsp;31, 2008, which include $63.6 million of loans from the Company to the ESOP, are reflected
as debt with a corresponding reduction of shareholders&#146; equity (additional paid-in capital included a balance of $56.4 million and $63.8 million at December&nbsp;31, 2008 and 2007, respectively). The ESOP is repaying the loans and interest
through 2018 using Company contributions and dividends from its McDonald&#146;s common stock holdings. As the principal amount of the borrowings is repaid, the debt and the unearned ESOP compensation (additional paid-in capital) are reduced.
</FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:11px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2"><B>EMPLOYEE BENEFIT PLANS </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:8px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P> <P
STYLE="line-height:0px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:2px;border-bottom:0.5pt solid #000000">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:2px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">The Company&#146;s Profit Sharing and Savings Plan for U.S.-based employees
includes a 401(k) feature, an ESOP feature, and a discretionary employer profit sharing match. The 401(k) feature allows participants to make pretax contributions that are partly matched from shares released under the ESOP. The Profit Sharing and
Savings Plan also provides for a discretionary employer profit sharing match after the end of the year for those participants eligible to share in the match who have contributed to the 401(k) feature. </FONT></P> <P
STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:19px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">All contributions and related earnings can be invested in several investment alternatives as well as McDonald&#146;s common stock </FONT></P></DIV><DIV
STYLE="position:relative;float:right; width:48%;padding-right:9px;padding-bottom:8px;overflow:hidden"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">
<FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">in accordance with each participant&#146;s elections. Beginning in 2007, participants&#146; annual contributions to the 401(k) feature and the discretionary employer
match are limited to 20% investment in McDonald&#146;s common stock. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:19px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">The Company also maintains certain supplemental benefit plans that allow
participants to (i)&nbsp;make tax-deferred contributions and (ii)&nbsp;receive Company-provided allocations that cannot be made under the Profit Sharing and Savings Plan because of Internal Revenue Service limitations. The investment alternatives
and returns are based on certain market-rate investment alternatives under the Profit Sharing and Savings Plan. Total liabilities were $389.7 million at December&nbsp;31, 2008 and $415.3 million at December&nbsp;31, 2007 and were primarily included
in other long-term liabilities on the Consolidated balance sheet. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:19px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">The Company has entered into derivative contracts to hedge market-driven changes
in certain of the liabilities. At December&nbsp;31, 2008, derivatives with a fair value of $90.2 million indexed to the Company&#146;s stock as well as an investment totaling $60.7 million indexed to certain market indices were included in
miscellaneous other assets on the Consolidated balance sheet. All changes in liabilities for these nonqualified plans and in the fair value of the derivatives are recorded in selling, general&nbsp;&amp; administrative expenses. Changes in fair value
of the derivatives indexed to the Company&#146;s stock are recorded in the income statement because the contracts provide the counterparty with a choice to settle in cash or shares. </FONT></P></DIV><br clear="All"> <P
STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P>
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px" ALIGN="right"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="1">45 </FONT></P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" COLOR="#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>

<DIV STYLE="position:relative;float:left; margin-right:1%; width:48%;padding-right:9px;padding-bottom:8px;overflow:hidden"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:19px">
<FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">Total U.S. costs for the Profit Sharing and Savings Plan, including nonqualified benefits and related hedging activities, were (in millions): 2008&#150;$61.2;
2007&#150;$57.6; 2006&#150;$60.1. Certain subsidiaries outside the U.S. also offer profit sharing, stock purchase or other similar benefit plans. Total plan costs outside the U.S. were (in millions): 2008&#150;$55.4; 2007&#150;$62.7;
2006&#150;$69.8. </FONT></P></DIV><DIV STYLE="position:relative;float:right; width:48%;padding-right:9px;padding-bottom:8px;overflow:hidden"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:19px">
<FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">The total combined liabilities for international retirement plans were $131.1 million and $129.4 million at December&nbsp;31, 2008 and 2007, respectively, primarily in
the U.K. and Canada. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:19px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">Other postretirement benefits and post-employment benefits were immaterial. </FONT></P></DIV><br clear="All"> <P
STYLE="font-size:11px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2"><B>SHARE-BASED COMPENSATION </B></FONT></P> <P
STYLE="font-size:8px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="line-height:0px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:2px;border-bottom:0.5pt solid #000000">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:2px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">The
Company maintains a share-based compensation plan which authorizes the granting of various equity-based incentives including stock options and restricted stock units (RSUs) to employees and nonemployee directors. The number of shares of common stock
reserved for issuance under the plans was 97.3&nbsp;million at December&nbsp;31, 2008, including 40.9&nbsp;million available for future grants. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:11px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2"><B>Stock options
</B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:2px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">Stock options to purchase common stock are granted with an exercise price equal to the closing market price of the Company&#146;s stock on the date of grant.
Substantially all of the options become exercisable in four equal installments, beginning a year from the date of the grant, and generally expire 10 years from the grant date. Options granted between May&nbsp;1, 1999 and December&nbsp;31, 2000
(approximately 11&nbsp;million options outstanding at December&nbsp;31, 2008) expire 13 years from the date of grant. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:3%"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">Intrinsic value for stock
options is defined as the difference between the current market value and the exercise price. During 2008, 2007 and 2006, the total intrinsic value of stock options exercised was $549.5 million, $815.3 million and $412.6 million, respectively. Cash
received from stock options exercised during 2008 was $548.2 million and the actual tax benefit realized for tax deductions from stock options exercised totaled $160.2 million. The Company uses treasury shares purchased under the Company&#146;s
share repurchase program to satisfy share-based exercises. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:3%"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">A summary of the status of the Company&#146;s stock option grants as of December&nbsp;31,
2008, 2007 and 2006, and changes during the years then ended, is presented in the following table: </FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:11px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P> <P
STYLE="line-height:0px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:2px;border-bottom:0.5pt solid #000000">&nbsp;</P>

<TD VALIGN="bottom"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom"></TD></TR>
</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:11px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2"><B>RSUs </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:2px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P><DIV
STYLE="position:relative;float:left; margin-right:1%; width:48%;padding-right:9px;padding-bottom:8px;overflow:hidden"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">RSUs generally vest 100% on the third anniversary of the
grant and are payable in either shares of McDonald&#146;s common stock or cash, at the Company&#146;s discretion. Certain executives have been awarded RSUs that vest based on Company performance. The fair value of each RSU granted is equal to the
market price of the </FONT></P></DIV><DIV STYLE="position:relative;float:right; width:48%;padding-right:9px;padding-bottom:8px;overflow:hidden"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">
<FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">Company&#146;s stock at date of grant less the present value of expected dividends over the vesting period. </FONT></P> <P
STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px; text-indent:19px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">A summary of the Company&#146;s RSU activity during the years ended December&nbsp;31, 2008, 2007 and 2006 is presented in the following table:

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="1"><I>Includes net pretax and after tax expense of $1.6 billion ($1.32 per share from continuing operations&#150;basic, $1.33 per share net income&#150;basic, $1.31 per share&#150;diluted)
related to the sale of Latam to a developmental licensee. </I></FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:4px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2"><B><A NAME="tx80436_33"></A>MANAGEMENT&#146;S ASSESSMENT OF INTERNAL CONTROL OVER FINANCIAL REPORTING </B></FONT></P> <P
STYLE="font-size:8px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="line-height:0px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:2px;border-bottom:0.5pt solid #000000">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:2px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">The
financial statements were prepared by management, which is responsible for their integrity and objectivity and for establishing and maintaining adequate internal controls over financial reporting. </FONT></P> <P
STYLE="margin-top:11px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">The Company&#146;s internal control over financial reporting is designed to provide reasonable assurance regarding the reliability of financial reporting and the preparation of
financial statements for external purposes in accordance with generally accepted accounting principles. The Company&#146;s internal control over financial reporting includes those policies and procedures that: </FONT></P> <P
STYLE="font-size:11px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">I.</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">pertain to the maintenance of records that, in reasonable detail, accurately and fairly reflect the transactions and dispositions of the assets of the Company; </FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> <P
STYLE="font-size:11px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">II.</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">provide reasonable assurance that transactions are recorded as necessary to permit preparation of financial statements in accordance with generally accepted accounting principles, and that
receipts and expenditures of the Company are being made only in accordance with authorizations of management and directors of the Company; and </FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:11px;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">III.</FONT></TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">provide reasonable assurance regarding prevention or timely detection of unauthorized acquisition, use or disposition of the Company&#146;s assets that could have a material effect on the
financial statements. </FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:11px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">There are inherent limitations in the effectiveness of any internal control, including the possibility of human error and the
circumvention or overriding of controls. Accordingly, even effective internal controls can provide only reasonable assurances with respect to financial statement preparation. Further, because of changes in conditions, the effectiveness of internal
controls may vary over time. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:11px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">Management assessed the design and effectiveness of the Company&#146;s internal control over financial reporting as of
December&nbsp;31, 2008. In making this assessment, management used the criteria set forth by the Committee of Sponsoring Organizations of the Treadway Commission (&#147;COSO&#148;) in Internal Control &#150; Integrated Framework. </FONT></P> <P
STYLE="margin-top:11px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">Based on management&#146;s assessment using those criteria, as of December&nbsp;31, 2008, management believes that the Company&#146;s internal control over financial reporting is
effective. </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:11px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">Ernst&nbsp;&amp; Young, LLP, independent registered public accounting firm, has audited the financial statements of the Company for the fiscal years
ended December&nbsp;31, 2008, 2007 and 2006 and the Company&#146;s internal control over financial reporting as of December&nbsp;31, 2008. Their reports are presented on the following pages. The independent registered public accountants and internal
auditors advise management of the results of their audits, and make recommendations to improve the system of internal controls. Management evaluates the audit recommendations and takes appropriate action. </FONT></P> <P
STYLE="margin-top:23px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">McDONALD&#146;S CORPORATION </FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE="2">February&nbsp;18, 2009 </FONT></P> <P
STYLE="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px"><FONT SIZE="1">&nbsp;</FONT></P>
